<HEADLINE>
TOTAL NUMBER OF CIVIL SERVANTS DOWN SLIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, Feb. 15 (CNA) 02/15/07  14:29:59 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
The number of civil servants in Taiwan totaled 335,274 as of the
end of 2006, with their age averaging 42.88 years, the Ministry
of Civil Service under the Examination Yuan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure marked a decrease of 1,987 from 337,261 at the end of
2005, mainly because of the continued streamlining of state-owned
enterprises and health institutions, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials made the remarks while delivering a report on the
manpower structure of the nation's civil service at the
Examination Yuan.
</P>
<P>
By level of government, there were 185,286 civil servants working
for the central government, accounting for 55.26 percent of the
total, and 149,988 civil servants working at local-level
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
By gender, men significantly outnumbered women, with a total of
211,374 of the civil servants, or 63.05 percent, being male.
</P>
<P>
The average age of the civil servants was 42.88 years, up 0.29
years from the average of 42.59 years at the end of 2005.
</P>
<P>
The average age of civil servants working for the central
government was 44.55 years, with their period of service
averaging 16.72 years, up 0.25 years from 16.47 years at the end
of 2005.
</P>
<P>
In terms of education background, civil servants with university
degrees and above accounted for 76.45 percent of the total.
</P>
